        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "Evil is described by Peck as \"militant ignorance\". The original [[Judeo-Christian]] concept of \"[[sin]]\" is as a process that leads us to \"miss the mark\" and fall short of perfection.<ref name=\"Liemult\" /> Peck argues that while most people are conscious of this, at least on some level, those that are evil actively and militantly refuse this consciousness. Peck considers those he calls evil to be attempting to escape and hide from their own conscience (through self-deception), and views this as being quite distinct from the apparent absence of conscience evident in sociopathy ([[Psychopathy]]).<ref name=\"Liemult\" />"
